Buffalo Chicken Wing Recipe

This recipe is best enjoyed in the fall.

Homemade Buffalo Wings

Ingredients

  • 1 to 4 pounds chicken wings
  • 1 1/2 to 2 teaspoons baking powder
  • 1 to 4 teaspoons kosher salt
  • 2 tablespoons hot sauce
  • 1 1/2 to 2 tablespoons unsalted butter

Tools

  • Baking sheet
  • Oven-safe cooling rack
  • Tongs
  • Medium saucepan

Instructions

  1. Line baking sheet with foil and set colling rack on top
  2. Pat wings dry and toss with baking powder and salt
  3. Place in regrigerator uncovered for 8 to 24 hours
  4. Heat ovens to 450 degrees and bake wings for 20 minutes
  5. Flip wings with tongs, bake for 15 minutes, flip them again, and then cook again for 15 minutes.
  6. Combine 2 tablespoons of hot sauce and 2 tablespoons of unsalted butter and heat until melted
  7. Roll each wing in sauce and serve with cellery or carrot

Blue Cheese Dressing Variation

Ingredients

  • 1/3 cup buttermilk
  • 1/3 cup mayonnaise
  • 1/3 cup sour cream
  • Juice of half a lemon
  • 2 teaspoons white vinegar
  • 1 small garlic clobe
  • Salt and pepper
  • 4 ounces blue cheese
  • 2 tablespoons olives

Instructions

  1. Combine ingridents in a bowl
  2. Stir until combined
  3. Season thoroughly with salt and pepper

The Euclidean distance between points p and q is the length of the line segment connecting them (\(\overline{\textbf{pq}}\)).

In Cartesian coordinates, if \(\textbf{p} = (p_1, p_2,..., p_n)\) and \(\textbf{q} = (q_1, q_2,..., q_n)\) are two points in Euclidean n-space, then the distance (d) from p to q, or from q to p is given by the Pythagorean formula:

\(\begin{equation}\label{eq:1}\begin{split} \textit{d}(\textbf{p, q}) = \textit{d}(\textbf{q, p}) & = \sqrt{(q_1 - p_1)^2 + (q_2 - p_2)^2 + \cdot\cdot\cdot + (q_n - p_n)^2} \\ & = \sqrt{\sum\limits_{i = 1}^{n} (q_i - p_i)^2} \end{split}\label{eq:2} \end{equation}\)

The position of a point in a Euclidean n-space is a Euclidean vector. So, p and q may be represented as Euclidean vectors, starting from the origin of the space (initial point) with their tips (terminal points) ending at the two points. The Euclidean norm, or Euclidean length, or magnitude of a vector measures the length of the vector:

\(\ \| \textbf{p} \| = \sqrt{p_1^2 + p_2^2 + \cdot\cdot\cdot + p_n^2} = \sqrt{\textbf{p} \cdot \textbf{p}}\)
